The main advantage of an improved substance is that it also takes on viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact prevails in some cases over the fact that the compound on the common variant of the virus does not act as strongly as some already available drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, patients can significantly prolong the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral replication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiwalled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Faulty and resistant virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease caused by the cleavage of the HIV virus, mature infectious viral particles would not occur.
When we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of drugs against HIV protease has been tested in the testicle and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on a common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, but its effect is not lost for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
