Turkish justice has dissolved for the Kurdish side and this decision has serious consequences for the Kurdish side.
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday decided to withdraw the main pro-Kurdish party in the country. This decision immediately sparked a protest in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and thus try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) has been dissolved because it has become "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The ruling was unanimously passed by 11 judges, who needed a majority of seven votes to dissolve the party, Kilic said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Turk and MP Aysela Tuglukov<0xC3><0xA1>, were banned from taking part in a political campaign.
At the same time, the judge announced the abolition of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. and Mrs. Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP side has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party's leadership has already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as MPs without political competence.
The decision is a continuation of the process initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the cassation court Abdurrahmane Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the “commandments” of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider to be terrorist organizations.
Many observers are convinced that the DTP is a legitimate political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party maintains that it has no “fundamental connection” with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict comes at a time when the government gives the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a number of measures to strengthen their rights and tries to limit the support of the Kurds against the PKK and end the conflict.
The leadership of the DTP confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a renewed tension in southeastern Anatolia, where in recent weeks many demonstrations have been thrown out against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan is detained in clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast, which is predominantly inhabited by Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, protesters threw Molotov cocktails again or fired stones from the works.
There were also hundreds of people in Istanbul.
After the verdict was delivered, Mr. Turk said that the decision of justice only "deepens the despair".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, ed.) by banning the party, he said in a press release.
The government, formed by the party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned this decision.
We are in principle against the interference of the parties.
It's not working, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete reflection of the democratic proposals initiated by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can wait for the reaction from the PKK, he added.
