75% of working mothers have labor problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially in women of younger age who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'The Fertility and Work Career of Spanish Women', conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market due to motherhood.
The study points out that at the beginning of the partnership, there are many differences in views on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with their partner earlier, give birth earlier, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone partner coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer descendants.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation with their partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have spent most of their stable employment and therefore had to postpone cohabitation.
The type of profession also has a strong impact on motherhood, although less impact on the time of beginning cohabitation with the partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of the marriage of the birth of the offspring is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25,1 or 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education get married and give birth to their first child even before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education, on the contrary, prefer to get a stable job, before marriage and the birth of the first child.
